300":"1300","1265":"1265","about 1300":"circa 1300","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1306":"1306","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cegidfan, Montgomery, Montgomery, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1270–":"1270–Deceased","1169–Male":"1169–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1304–Male":"1304–Deceased","1306–Male":"1306–Deceased","1314–Female":"1314–Deceased","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","from 1300 to 1320":"from 1300 to 1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1265":"1265","about 1300":"about 1300","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1306":"1306","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cegidfan, Montgomery, Montgomery, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madoc","type":"LAST","meanings":["The English form of the Welsh name Madawg."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Kadwgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joyce Madoc ap Kadwgan Wenwin was born in 1270, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Madog ap Hywel, was 46 and her mother, Arddun verch Rhys, was 6. She married David Edward Scriven about 1300, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","from 1300 to 1320":"1300 kuni 1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1265":"1265","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1306":"1306","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cegidfan, Montgomery, Montgomery, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1270–":"1270–Kuollut","1169–Male":"1169–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1304–Male":"1304–Kuollut","1306–Male":"1306–Kuollut","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","from 1300 to 1320":"vuodesta 1300 vuoteen 1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1265":"1265","about 1300":"noin 1300","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1306":"1306","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cegidfan, Montgomery, Montgomery, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1270–":"1270–Décédée","1169–Male":"1169–Décédé","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1304–Male"